# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ballerina-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] The project began in 2015 by architects from WSO2 as a code-based alternative to the configuration-based integration tools such as enterprise application integration (EAI), enterprise service bus (ESB), and workflow products.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] It has various constructs for cloud-native development including support for various data formats and protocols, reliability, distributed transactions, application programming interfaces (APIs), and event streams.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] Ballerina was first publicly announced in 2017 and version 1.0 was released on September 10, 2019.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] Ballerina is a general-purpose language with a familiar syntax along with a direct graphical representation of the code in the form of sequence diagrams.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] It has fundamental abstractions designed to make integration problems easier to program.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] Ballerina was designed by WSO2 to improve productivity for application developers that have to work with distributed computing.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] It is easy to write and modify and is suitable for application programmers.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] The designers, who provided enterprise integration products for over 10 years, used their knowledge of the industry when designing the language, says WSO2 director and Ballerina founder James Clark.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] To execute the above program, place the source code in a `.bal` file and provide the path of the file to the `bal run` command.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] Services are executed in the same manner, except they don't terminate like regular programs do.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] Once the service is up and running, one can use an HTTP client to invoke the service.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] The generated sequence diagram is a canonical representation of the source code.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] The two representations can be used interchangeably.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] The diagram support is provided through the Ballerina VS Code plugin.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] The following are a couple of such generated sequence diagrams, compared with its associated code.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] The language provides support for working with JSON values.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] Docker and Kubernetes artifacts required for deploying the code to the cloud can be generated when building the code.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] Values required for these artifacts are derived from the code.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] Additionally, one can override these values as well using the `Cloud.toml` file.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] To enable generation of the cloud artifacts, the users can use the `cloud` build option in the `Ballerina.toml` file.
[src:ballerina-deep/ballerina-programming-language] Use `docker` to generate just the Docker image and the Dockerfile and use `k8s` to generate Kubernetes artifacts as well.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:ballerina-deep/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] This is a property of a system—whether a program, computer, or a network—where there is a separate execution point or "thread of control" for each process.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] A *concurrent system* is one where a computation can advance without waiting for all other computations to complete.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computing is a form of modular programming.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] In its paradigm an overall computation is factored into subcomputations that may be executed concurrently.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Pioneers in the field of concurrent computing include Edsger Dijkstra, Per Brinch Hansen, and C.A.R.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] The concept of concurrent computing is frequently confused with the related but distinct concept of parallel computing, although both can be described as "multiple processes executing *during the same period of time*".
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] By contrast, concurrent computing consists of process *lifetimes* overlapping, but execution does not happen at the same instant.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] The goal here is to model processes that happen concurrently, like multiple clients accessing a server at the same time.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Structuring software systems as composed of multiple concurrent, communicating parts can be useful for tackling complexity, regardless of whether the parts can be executed in parallel.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] In this way, multiple processes are part-way through execution at a single instant, but only one process is being executed at that instant.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computations *may* be executed in parallel, for example, by assigning each process to a separate processor or processor core, or distributing a computation across a network.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] The exact timing of when tasks in a concurrent system are executed depends on the scheduling, and tasks need not always be executed concurrently.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] The word "sequential" is used as an antonym for both "concurrent" and "parallel"; when these are explicitly distinguished, *concurrent/sequential* and *parallel/serial* are used as opposing pairs.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] A schedule in which tasks execute one at a time (serially, no parallelism), without interleaving (sequentially, no concurrency: no task begins until the prior task ends) is called a *serial schedule*.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] A set of tasks that can be scheduled serially is *serializable*, which simplifies concurrency control.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] The main challenge in designing concurrent programs is concurrency control: ensuring the correct sequencing of the interactions or communications between different computational executions, and coordinating access to resources that are shared among executions.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Potential problems include race conditions, deadlocks, and resource starvation.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Suppose `balance = 500`, and two concurrent *threads* make the calls `withdraw(300)` and `withdraw(350)`.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] If line 3 in both operations executes before line 5 both operations will find that `balance >= withdrawal` evaluates to `true`, and execution will proceed to subtracting the withdrawal amount.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] However, since both processes perform their withdrawals, the total amount withdrawn will end up being more than the original balance.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] These sorts of problems with shared resources benefit from the use of concurrency control, or non-blocking algorithms.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Introduced in 1962, Petri nets were an early attempt to codify the rules of concurrent execution.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Dataflow theory later built upon these, and Dataflow architectures were created to physically implement the ideas of dataflow theory.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Beginning in the late 1970s, process calculi such as Calculus of Communicating Systems (CCS) and Communicating Sequential Processes (CSP) were developed to permit algebraic reasoning about systems composed of interacting components.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] The π-calculus added the capability for reasoning about dynamic topologies.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Input/output automata were introduced in 1987.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Logics such as Lamport's TLA+, and mathematical models such as traces and Actor event diagrams, have also been developed to describe the behavior of concurrent systems.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Software transactional memory borrows from database theory the concept of atomic transactions and applies them to memory accesses.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Concurrent programming languages and multiprocessor programs must have a consistency model (also known as a memory model).
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] The consistency model defines rules for how operations on computer memory occur and how results are produced.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] One of the first consistency models was Leslie Lamport's sequential consistency model.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Sequential consistency is the property of a program that its execution produces the same results as a sequential program.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Specifically, a program is sequentially consistent if "the results of any execution is the same as if the operations of all the processors were executed in some sequential order, and the operations of each individual processor appear in this sequence in the order specified by its program".
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] A number of different methods can be used to implement concurrent programs, such as implementing each computational execution as an operating system process, or implementing the computational processes as a set of threads within a single operating system process.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] In some concurrent computing systems, communication between the concurrent components is hidden from the programmer (e.g., by using futures), while in others it must be handled explicitly.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] The exchange of messages may be carried out asynchronously, or may use a synchronous "rendezvous" style in which the sender blocks until the message is received.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Asynchronous message passing may be reliable or unreliable (sometimes referred to as "send and pray").
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Message-passing concurrency tends to be far easier to reason about than shared-memory concurrency, and is typically considered a more robust form of concurrent programming.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Shared memory and message passing concurrency have different performance characteristics.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Typically (although not always), the per-process memory overhead and task switching overhead is lower in a message passing system, but the overhead of message passing is greater than for a procedure call.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] These differences are often overwhelmed by other performance factors.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computing developed out of earlier work on railroads and telegraphy, from the 19th and early 20th century, and some terms date to this period, such as semaphores.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] These arose to address the question of how to handle multiple trains on the same railroad system (avoiding collisions and maximizing efficiency) and how to handle multiple transmissions over a given set of wires (improving efficiency), such as via time-division multiplexing (1870s).
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] The academic study of concurrent algorithms started in the 1960s, with Dijkstra (1965) credited with being the first paper in this field, identifying and solving mutual exclusion.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Concurrency is pervasive in computing, occurring from low-level hardware on a single chip to worldwide networks.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] At the network level, networked systems are generally concurrent by their nature, as they consist of separate devices.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Concurrent programming languages are programming languages that use language constructs for concurrency.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] These constructs may involve multi-threading, support for distributed computing, message passing, shared resources (including shared memory) or futures and promises.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Such languages are sometimes described as *concurrency-oriented languages* or *concurrency-oriented programming languages* (COPL).
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Today, the most commonly used programming languages that have specific constructs for concurrency are Java and C#.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Both of these languages fundamentally use a shared-memory concurrency model, with locking provided by monitors (although message-passing models can and have been implemented on top of the underlying shared-memory model).
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Of the languages that use a message-passing concurrency model, Erlang was probably the most widely used in industry as of 2010.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Many concurrent programming languages have been developed more as research languages (e.g., Pict) rather than as languages for production use.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] However, languages such as Erlang, Limbo, and occam have seen industrial use at various times in the last 20 years.
[src:ballerina-deep/concurrent-computing] Many other languages provide support for concurrency in the form of libraries, at levels roughly comparable with the above list.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] A **domain-specific language** (**DSL**) is a computer language specialized to a specific application domain.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] This is in contrast to a general-purpose language (GPL), which is broadly applicable across domains.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] There are a wide variety of DSLs, ranging from widely used languages for common domains, such as HTML for web pages, down to languages used by only one or a few pieces of software, such as MUSH soft code.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] DSLs can be further subdivided by the kind of language, and include domain-specific *markup* languages, domain-specific *modeling* languages (more generally, specification languages), and domain-specific *programming* languages.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Special-purpose computer languages have always existed in the computer age, but the term "domain-specific language" has become more popular due to the rise of domain-specific modeling.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Simpler DSLs, specifically ones used by a single application, are sometimes informally called **mini-languages**.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] For example, Perl was originally developed as a text-processing and glue language, for the same domain as AWK and shell scripts, but was mostly used as a general-purpose programming language later on.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] In contrast, PostScript is a Turing-complete language, and in principle can be used for any task, but in practice is narrowly used as a page description language.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] The design and use of appropriate DSLs is a key part of domain engineering, by using a language suitable to the domain at hand – this may consist of using an existing DSL or GPL, or developing a new DSL.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Language-oriented programming considers the creation of special-purpose languages for expressing problems as standard part of the problem-solving process.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Pragmatically, a DSL may be specialized to a specific problem domain, a specific problem representation technique, a specific solution technique, or other aspects of a domain.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is created specifically to solve problems in a specific domain and is not intended to be able to solve problems outside of it (although that may be technically possible).
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] In contrast, general-purpose languages are created to solve problems in many domains.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is somewhere between a tiny programming language and a scripting language, and is often used in a way analogous to a programming library.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] The boundaries between these concepts are quite blurry, much like the boundary between scripting languages and general-purpose languages.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages are languages (or often, declared syntaxes or grammars) with very specific goals in design and implementation.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language can be one of a visual diagramming language, such as those created by the Generic Eclipse Modeling System, programmatic abstractions, such as the Eclipse Modeling Framework, or textual languages.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] For instance, the command line utility grep has a regular expression syntax which matches patterns in lines of text.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] The sed utility defines a syntax for matching and replacing regular expressions.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Often, these tiny languages can be used together inside a shell to perform more complex programming tasks.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] The line between domain-specific languages and scripting languages is somewhat blurred, but domain-specific languages often lack low-level functions for file system access, interprocess control, and other functions that characterize full-featured programming languages, scripting or otherwise.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Further blurring this line, many domain-specific languages have exposed APIs, and can be accessed from other programming languages without breaking the flow of execution or calling a separate process, and can thus operate as programming libraries.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Some domain-specific languages expand over time to include full-featured programming tools, which further complicates the question of whether a language is domain-specific or not.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] In model-driven engineering, many examples of domain-specific languages may be found like Object Constraint Language (OCL), a language for decorating models with assertions or Query/View/Transformation (QVT), a domain-specific transformation language.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] However, languages like Unified Modeling Language (UML) are typically general-purpose modeling languages.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] To summarize, an analogy is useful: a *very little language* is like a knife, which can be used in thousands of different ways, from cutting food to self-defense.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] A *domain-specific language* is like an electric drill: it is a powerful tool with a wide variety of uses, but a specific context, namely, making holes in things.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] A *general purpose language* is a complete workbench, with a variety of tools intended for performing a variety of tasks.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages should be used by programmers who, looking at their current workbench, realize they need a better drill and find that a given domain-specific language provides exactly that.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] DSLs implemented via an independent interpreter or compiler are termed *external domain specific languages*.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] A separate category termed *embedded (or internal) domain specific languages* are typically implemented within a host language as a library and tend to be limited to the syntax of the host language, though this depends on host language abilities.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Adopting a domain-specific language approach to software engineering involves both risks and opportunities.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] The well-designed domain-specific language manages to find the proper balance between these.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] GML is a domain-specific language used by GameMaker Studio designed to help novice programmers learn the fundamentals of coding more easily.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] It functions as a blend of several languages, including Delphi, C++, and BASIC.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Most GML functions, once compiled, call runtime functions written in the specific language of the target platform; consequently, their final implementation remains hidden from the user.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] The language's primary goal is to lower the barrier to entry for game development.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] The GameMaker runtime, which manages the main game loop and handles function implementation, allows a simple game to use only a few lines of code instead of thousands.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] ColdFusion's associated scripting language is another example of a domain-specific language for data-driven websites.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] The language is used to weave together languages and services such as Java, .NET, C++, SMS, email, email servers, http, ftp, exchange, directory services, and file systems for use in websites.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] The ColdFusion Markup Language (CFML) includes a set of tags that can be used in ColdFusion pages to interact with data sources, manipulate data, and display output.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] CFML tag syntax is similar to HTML element syntax.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Although the FilterMeister language reproduces a significant portion of the C language and function library, it contains only those features which can be used within the context of Photoshop plug-ins and adds a number of specific features only useful in this specific domain.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] The *Template* feature of MediaWiki is an embedded domain-specific language whose fundamental purpose is to support the creation of page templates and the transclusion (inclusion by reference) of MediaWiki pages into other MediaWiki pages.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] There has been much interest in domain-specific languages to improve the productivity and quality of software engineering.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific language could possibly provide a robust set of tools for efficient software engineering.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Such tools are beginning to make their way into the development of critical software systems.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] The Software Cost Reduction Toolkit is an example of this.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] A newer development is language-oriented programming, an integrated software engineering methodology based mainly on creating, optimizing, and using domain-specific languages.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Complementing language-oriented programming, and all other forms of domain-specific languages, are the class of compiler writing tools called metacompilers.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Such compiler is useful for generating parsers and code generators for domain-specific languages, and a metacompiler compiles a domain-specific metalanguage specifically designed for the domain of metaprogramming.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Besides parsing domain-specific languages, metacompilers are useful for generating a wide range of software engineering and analysis tools.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] The meta-compiler methodology is often found in program transformation systems.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Metacompilers that played a significant role in both computer science and the computer industry include META II, and its descendant TreeMeta.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Unreal and Unreal Tournament unveiled a language named UnrealScript.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] This allowed rapid development of modifications relative to the competitor Quake (using the Id Tech 2 engine).
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] The Id Tech engine used standard C code meaning C had to be learned and properly applied, while UnrealScript was optimized for ease of use and efficiency.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Similarly, more recent games have introduced their own specific languages for development.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] One more common example is Lua for scripting.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Various business rules engines have been developed for automating policy and business rules used in both government and private industry.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] ILOG, Oracle Policy Automation, DTRules, Drools and others provide support for DSLs aimed to support various problem domains.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] DTRules goes so far as to define an interface for the use of multiple DSLs within a rule set.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] The purpose of business rules engines is to define a representation of business logic in as human-readable fashion as possible.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] This allows both subject-matter experts and developers to work with and understand the same representation of the business logic.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Most rules engines provide both an approach to simplifying the control structures for business logic (for example, using declarative rules or decision tables) coupled with alternatives to programming syntax in favor of DSLs.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Statistical modelers have developed domain-specific languages such as R (an implementation of the S language), Bugs, Jags, and Stan.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] These languages provide a syntax for describing a Bayesian model and generate a method for solving it using simulation.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Generate object handling and services based on an Interface Description Language for a domain-specific language such as JavaScript for web applications, HTML for documentation, C++ for high-performance code, etc.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] This is done by cross-language frameworks such as Apache Thrift or Google Protocol Buffers.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Gherkin is a language designed to define test cases to check the behavior of software, without specifying how that behavior is implemented.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] It is meant to be read and used by non-technical users using a natural language syntax and a line-oriented design.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] The tests defined with Gherkin must then be implemented in a general programming language.
[src:ballerina-deep/domain-specific-language] Then, the steps in a Gherkin program acts as a syntax for method invocation accessible to non-developers.
[src:ballerina-deep/integration-platform] An **integration platform** is software which integrates different applications and services.
[src:ballerina-deep/integration-platform] It differentiates itself from the enterprise application integration which has a focus on supply chain management.
[src:ballerina-deep/integration-platform] It uses the idea of system integration to create an environment for engineers.
[src:ballerina-deep/integration-platform] It connects different systems to enable them to share data and information.
[src:ballerina-deep/integration-platform] Integration platforms can be built from components, purchased as a pre-built product ready for installation or procured from an integration Platform as a Service (iPaaS) company.
[src:ballerina-deep/integration-platform] An integration platform has a focus to be designed by and helpful to engineers.
[src:ballerina-deep/integration-platform] It has no intention to map business processes or integrate tools for supply chain management.
[src:ballerina-deep/integration-platform] Therefore, it is not related to those systems.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] A programming language consists of a system of allowed sequences of symbols (constructs) together with rules that define how each construct is interpreted.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For example, a language might allow expressions representing various types of data, expressions that provide structuring rules for data, expressions representing various operations on data, and constructs that provide sequencing rules for the order in which to perform operations.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] A simple type system for a programming language is a set of rules that associates a *data type* (for example, integer, floating point, string) with each *term* (data-valued expression) in a computer program.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In more ambitious type systems, a variety of constructs, such as variables, expressions, functions, and modules, may be assigned types.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Type systems formalize and enforce the otherwise implicit categories the programmer uses for algebraic data types, data structures, or other data types, such as "string", "array of float", "function returning boolean".
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The main purpose of a type system in a programming language is to reduce possibilities for bugs in computer programs due to mismatches in how values are interpreted in different parts of a program.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The aim is to prevent operations expecting a certain kind of value from being applied to values for which that operation does not make sense (validity errors).
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] A type system can detect and prevent some of these mismatches.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] When a type mismatch is detected, it is called a type error.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The type of a term constrains the contexts in which it may be used.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For a variable, the type system determines the allowed values of that variable.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For that variable to be presented as a parameter to an operation, the operation must be able to accept in that parameter any value that the type of the variable allows.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Type systems are typically specified as part of programming language design.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] They are built into interpreters and compilers for the language.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In some languages, the type system can be extended by optional tools that perform added checks using the language's original type syntax and grammar.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Type systems allow defining interfaces between different parts of a computer program, and then checking that the parts have been connected in a consistent way.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] This checking can happen statically (at compile time), dynamically (at runtime), or as a combination of both.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Type systems have other purposes as well, such as expressing business rules, enabling certain compiler optimizations, allowing for multiple dispatch, and providing a form of documentation.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] An example of a simple type system is that of the C language.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The portions of a C program are the function definitions.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] One function is invoked by another function.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The interface of a function states the name of the function and a list of parameters that are passed to the function's code.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The code of an invoking function states the name of the invoked, along with the names of variables that hold values to pass to it.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] During a computer program's execution, the values are placed into temporary storage, then execution jumps to the code of the invoked function.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The invoked function's code accesses the values and makes use of them.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] If the instructions inside the function are written with the assumption of receiving an integer value, but the calling code passed a floating-point value, then the wrong result will be computed by the invoked function.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The C compiler checks the types of the arguments passed to a function when it is called against the types of the parameters declared in the function's definition.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] If the types do not match, the compiler throws a compile-time error or warning.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] A compiler may also use the static type of a value to optimize the storage it needs and the choice of algorithms for operations on the value.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In many C compilers the *float* data type, for example, is represented in 32 bits, in accord with the IEEE specification for single-precision floating point numbers.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] They will thus use floating-point-specific microprocessor operations on those values (floating-point addition, multiplication, etc.).
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The depth of type constraints and the manner of their evaluation affect the *typing* of the language.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] A programming language may further associate an operation with various resolutions for each type, in the case of type polymorphism.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Type theory is the study of type systems.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The concrete types of some programming languages, such as integers and strings, depend on practical issues of computer architecture, compiler implementation, and language design.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Formally, type theory studies type systems.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] A programming language must have the opportunity to type check using the *type system* whether at compile time or runtime, manually annotated or automatically inferred.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Assigning a data type, termed *typing*, gives meaning to a sequence of bits such as a value in memory or some object such as a variable.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Associating a sequence of bits with a type conveys that meaning to the programmable hardware to form a *symbolic system* composed of that hardware and some program.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] A program associates each value with at least one specific type, but it also can occur that one value is associated with many subtypes.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Other entities, such as objects, modules, communication channels, and dependencies can become associated with a type.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Even a type can become associated with a type.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] An implementation of a *type system* could in theory associate identifications called *data type* (a type of a value), *class* (a type of an object), and *kind* (a *type of a type*, or metatype).
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] These are the abstractions that typing can go through, on a hierarchy of levels contained in a system.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] It is challenging to find a sufficiently expressive type system that satisfies all programming practices in a type safe manner.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] A programming language compiler can also implement a *dependent type* or an *effect system*, which enables even more program specifications to be verified by a type checker.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Beyond simple value-type pairs, a virtual "region" of code is associated with an "effect" component describing *what* is being done *with what*, and enabling for example to "throw" an error report.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Thus the symbolic system may be a *type and effect system*, which endows it with more safety checking than type checking alone.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Whether automated by the compiler or specified by a programmer, a type system renders program behavior illegal if it falls outside the type-system rules.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] A type error occurs when an operation receives a different type of data than it expected.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For example, a type error would happen if a line of code divides two integers, and is passed a string of letters instead of an integer.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] It is an unintended condition which might manifest in multiple stages of a program's development.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Thus a facility for detection of the error is needed in the type system.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In some languages, such as Haskell, for which type inference is automated, lint might be available to its compiler to aid in the detection of error.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Type safety contributes to program correctness, but might only guarantee correctness at the cost of making the type checking itself an undecidable problem (as in the halting problem).
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In a *type system* with automated type checking, a program may prove to run incorrectly yet produce no compiler errors.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Division by zero is an unsafe and incorrect operation, but a type checker which only runs at compile time does not scan for division by zero in most languages; that division would surface as a runtime error.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] To prove the absence of these defects, other kinds of formal methods, collectively known as program analyses, are in common use.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Alternatively, a sufficiently expressive type system, such as in dependently typed languages, can prevent these kinds of errors (for example, expressing *the type of non-zero numbers*).
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In addition, software testing is an empirical method for finding errors that such a type checker would not detect.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The process of verifying and enforcing the constraints of types, *type checking*, may occur at compile time (a static check) or at runtime (a dynamic check).
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] If a language specification requires its typing rules strongly, more or less allowing only those automatic type conversions that do not lose information, one can refer to the process as *strongly typed*; if not, as *weakly typed*.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The terms are not usually used in a strict sense.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Static type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program based on analysis of a program's text (source code).
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] If a program passes a static type checker, then the program is guaranteed to satisfy some set of type safety properties for all possible inputs.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Static type checking can be considered a limited form of program verification (see type safety), and in a type-safe language, can also be considered an optimization.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] If a compiler can prove that a program is well-typed, then it does not need to emit dynamic safety checks, allowing the resulting compiled binary to run faster and to be smaller.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Static type checking for Turing-complete languages is inherently conservative.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Even if the expression `<complex test>` always evaluates to `true` at runtime, most type checkers will reject the program as ill-typed, because it is difficult (if not impossible) for a static analyzer to determine that the `else` branch will not be taken.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Consequently, a static type checker will quickly detect type errors in rarely used code paths.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Without static type checking, even code coverage tests with 100% coverage may be unable to find such type errors.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The tests may fail to detect such type errors, because the combination of all places where values are created and all places where a certain value is used must be taken into account.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] A number of useful and common programming language features cannot be checked statically, such as downcasting.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Thus, many languages will have both static and dynamic type checking; the static type checker verifies what it can, and dynamic checks verify the rest.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Many languages with static type checking provide a way to bypass the type checker.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Some languages allow programmers to choose between static and dynamic type safety.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For example, historically C# declares variables statically, but C# 4.0 introduces the `dynamic` keyword, which is used to declare variables to be checked dynamically at runtime.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Other languages allow writing code that is not type-safe; for example, in C, programmers can freely cast a value between any two types that have the same size, effectively subverting the type concept.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Dynamic type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program at runtime.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Implementations of dynamically type-checked languages generally associate each runtime object with a *type tag* (i.e., a reference to a type) containing its type information.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] This runtime type information (RTTI) can also be used to implement dynamic dispatch, late binding, downcasting, reflective programming (reflection), and similar features.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Most type-safe languages include some form of dynamic type checking, even if they also have a static type checker.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The reason for this is that many useful features or properties are difficult or impossible to verify statically.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For example, suppose that a program defines two types, A and B, where B is a subtype of A.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] If the program tries to convert a value of type A to type B, which is known as downcasting, then the operation is legal only if the value being converted is actually a value of type B.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Thus, a dynamic check is needed to verify that the operation is safe.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] This requirement is one of the criticisms of downcasting.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] By definition, dynamic type checking may cause a program to fail at runtime.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In some programming languages, it is possible to anticipate and recover from these failures.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In others, type-checking errors are considered fatal.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Programming languages that include dynamic type checking but not static type checking are often called "dynamically typed programming languages".
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Certain languages allow both static and dynamic typing.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For example, Java and some other ostensibly statically typed languages support downcasting types to their subtypes, querying an object to discover its dynamic type and other type operations that depend on runtime type information.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] More generally, most programming languages include mechanisms for dispatching over different 'kinds' of data, such as disjoint unions, runtime polymorphism, and variant types.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Even when not interacting with type annotations or type checking, such mechanisms are materially similar to dynamic typing implementations.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Objects in object-oriented languages are usually accessed by a reference whose static target type (or manifest type) is equal to either the object's runtime type (its latent type) or a supertype thereof.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] This is conformant with the Liskov substitution principle, which states that all operations performed on an instance of a given type can also be performed on an instance of a subtype.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] This concept is also known as subsumption or subtype polymorphism.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In some languages subtypes may also possess covariant or contravariant return types and argument types respectively.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Certain languages, for example Clojure, Common Lisp, or Cython are dynamically type checked by default, but allow programs to opt into static type checking by providing optional annotations.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] One reason to use such hints would be to optimize the performance of critical sections of a program.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The programming environment *DrRacket*, a pedagogic environment based on Lisp, and a precursor of the language Racket is also soft-typed.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Conversely, as of version 4.0, the C# language provides a way to indicate that a variable should not be statically type checked.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] A variable whose type is `dynamic` will not be subject to static type checking.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Instead, the program relies on runtime type information to determine how the variable may be used.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In Rust, the `dyn std::any::Any` trait object provides dynamic typing of types containing no or only `'static` lifetimes.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The choice between static and dynamic typing requires certain trade-offs.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Static typing can find type errors reliably at compile time, which increases the reliability of the delivered program.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] However, programmers disagree over how commonly type errors occur, resulting in further disagreements over the proportion of those bugs that are coded that would be caught by appropriately representing the designed types in code.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Static typing advocates believe programs are more reliable when they have been well type-checked, whereas dynamic-typing advocates point to distributed code that has proven reliable and to small bug databases.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The value of static typing increases as the strength of the type system is increased.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Advocates of dependent typing, implemented in languages such as Dependent ML and Epigram, have suggested that almost all bugs can be considered type errors, if the types used in a program are properly declared by the programmer or correctly inferred by the compiler.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Static typing usually results in compiled code that executes faster.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] When the compiler knows the exact data types that are in use (which is necessary for static verification, either through declaration or inference) it can produce optimized machine code.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Some dynamically typed languages such as Common Lisp allow optional type declarations for optimization for this reason.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] By contrast, dynamic typing may allow compilers to run faster and interpreters to dynamically load new code, because changes to source code in dynamically typed languages may result in less checking to perform and less code to revisit.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] This too may reduce the edit-compile-test-debug cycle.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Statically typed languages that lack type inference (such as C and Java prior to version 10) require that programmers declare the types that a method or function must use.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] This can serve as added program documentation, that is active and dynamic, instead of static.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] This allows a compiler to prevent it from drifting out of synchrony, and from being ignored by programmers.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] However, a language can be statically typed without requiring type declarations (examples include Haskell, Scala, OCaml, F#, Swift, and to a lesser extent C# and C++), so explicit type declaration is not required for static typing in all languages.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Dynamic typing allows constructs that some (simple) static type checking would reject as illegal.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For example, *eval* functions, which execute arbitrary data as code, become possible.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] An *eval* function is possible with static typing, but requires advanced uses of algebraic data types.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Further, dynamic typing better accommodates transitional code and prototyping, such as allowing a placeholder data structure (mock object) to be transparently used in place of a full data structure (usually for the purposes of experimentation and testing).
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Dynamic typing typically allows duck typing (which enables easier code reuse).
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Many languages with static typing also feature duck typing or other mechanisms like generic programming that also enable easier code reuse.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Dynamic typing typically makes metaprogramming easier to use.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For example, C++ templates are typically more cumbersome to write than the equivalent Ruby or Python code since C++ has stronger rules regarding type definitions (for both functions and variables).
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] This forces a developer to write more boilerplate code for a template than a Python developer would need to.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] More advanced runtime constructs such as metaclasses and introspection are often harder to use in statically typed languages.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In some languages, such features may also be used e.g. to generate new types and behaviors on the fly, based on runtime data.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Such advanced constructs are often provided by dynamic programming languages; many of these are dynamically typed, although *dynamic typing* need not be related to *dynamic programming languages*.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Languages are often colloquially referred to as *strongly typed* or *weakly typed*.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In fact, there is no universally accepted definition of what these terms mean.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In general, there are more precise terms to represent the differences between type systems that lead people to call them "strong" or "weak".
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] A third way of categorizing the type system of a programming language is by the safety of typed operations and conversions.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *type-safe language* to describe languages that do not allow operations or conversions that violate the rules of the type system.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *memory-safe language* (or just *safe language*) to describe languages that do not allow programs to access memory that has not been assigned for their use.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For example, a memory-safe language will check array bounds, or else statically guarantee (i.e., at compile time before execution) that array accesses out of the array boundaries will cause compile-time and perhaps runtime errors.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In this example, the variable `z` will have the value 42.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Although this may not be what the programmer anticipated, it is a well-defined result.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] If `y` were a different string, one that could not be converted to a number (e.g., "Hello, World"), the result would be well-defined also.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] A program can be type-safe or memory-safe and still crash on an invalid operation.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] This is for languages where the type system is not sufficiently advanced to precisely specify the validity of operations on all possible operands.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] But if a program encounters an operation that is not type-safe, terminating the program is often the only option.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In this example `z` will point to a memory address five characters beyond `y`, equivalent to three characters after the terminating zero character of the string pointed to by `y`.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] This is memory that the program is not expected to access.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In C terms this is simply undefined behaviour and the program may do anything; with a simple compiler it might actually print whatever byte is stored after the string "37".
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] As this example shows, C is not memory-safe.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] As arbitrary data was assumed to be a character, it is also not a type-safe language.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In general, type-safety and memory-safety go hand in hand.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For example, a language that supports pointer arithmetic and number-to-pointer conversions (like C) is neither memory-safe nor type-safe, because it allows arbitrary memory to be accessed as if it were valid memory of any type.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Some languages allow different levels of checking to apply to different regions of code.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Additional tools such as lint and IBM Rational Purify can also be used to achieve a higher level of strictness.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] It has been proposed, chiefly by Gilad Bracha, that the choice of type system be made independent of choice of language; that a type system should be a module that can be *plugged* into a language as needed.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] He believes this is advantageous, because what he calls mandatory type systems make languages less expressive and code more fragile.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The requirement that the type system does not affect the semantics of the language is difficult to fulfill.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Optional typing is related to, but distinct from, gradual typing.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] While both typing disciplines can be used to perform static analysis of code (static typing), optional type systems do not enforce type safety at runtime (dynamic typing).
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The term *polymorphism* refers to the ability of code (especially, functions or classes) to act on values of multiple types, or to the ability of different instances of the same data structure to contain elements of different types.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Type systems that allow polymorphism generally do so to improve the potential for code re-use: in a language with polymorphism, programmers need only implement a data structure such as a list or an associative array once, rather than once for each type of element with which they plan to use it.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For this reason computer scientists sometimes call the use of certain forms of polymorphism *generic programming*.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The type-theoretic foundations of polymorphism are closely related to those of abstraction, modularity and (in some cases) subtyping.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Many type systems have been created that are specialized for use in certain environments with certain types of data, or for out-of-band static program analysis.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Frequently, these are based on ideas from formal type theory and are only available as part of prototype research systems.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The following table gives an overview over type theoretic concepts that are used in specialized type systems.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The names M, N, O range over terms and the names $\sigma ,\tau$ range over types.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Also referred to as *dependent sum type*, since ${\textstyle (x:\sigma )\times \tau =\sum _{x:\sigma }\tau }$ .
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Dependent types are based on the idea of using scalars or values to more precisely describe the type of some other value.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For example, $\mathrm {matrix} (3,3)$ might be the type of a $3\times 3$ matrix.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] where k, m, n are arbitrary positive integer values.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] A variant of ML called Dependent ML has been created based on this type system, but because type checking for conventional dependent types is undecidable, not all programs using them can be type-checked without some kind of limits.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Dependent ML limits the sort of equality it can decide to Presburger arithmetic.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Other languages such as Epigram make the value of all expressions in the language decidable so that type checking can be decidable.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] However, in general proof of decidability is undecidable, so many programs require hand-written annotations that may be very non-trivial.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] As this impedes the development process, many language implementations provide an easy way out in the form of an option to disable this condition.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] This, however, comes at the cost of making the type-checker run in an infinite loop when fed programs that do not type-check, causing the compilation to fail.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Linear types, based on the theory of linear logic, and closely related to uniqueness types, are types assigned to values having the property that they have one and only one reference to them at all times.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] These are valuable for describing large immutable values such as files, strings, and so on, because any operation that simultaneously destroys a linear object and creates a similar object (such as `str = str + "a"`) can be optimized "under the hood" into an in-place mutation.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Normally this is not possible, as such mutations could cause side effects on parts of the program holding other references to the object, violating referential transparency.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] They are also used in the prototype operating system Singularity for interprocess communication, statically ensuring that processes cannot share objects in shared memory to prevent race conditions.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The Clean language (a Haskell-like language) uses this type system to gain a lot of speed (compared to performing a deep copy) while remaining safe.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Intersection types are types describing values that belong to *both* of two other given types with overlapping value sets.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For example, in most implementations of C the signed char has range -128 to 127 and the unsigned char has range 0 to 255, so the intersection type of these two types would have range 0 to 127.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Such an intersection type could be safely passed into functions expecting *either* signed or unsigned chars, because it is compatible with both types.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Such a function could be passed into another function expecting an "`int` → `int`" function safely; it simply would not use the "`float` → `float`" functionality.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the intersection of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the most derived type.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The intersection of sibling types is empty.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The Forsythe language includes a general implementation of intersection types.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Union types are types describing values that belong to *either* of two types.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For example, in C, the signed char has a -128 to 127 range, and the unsigned char has a 0 to 255 range, so the union of these two types would have an overall "virtual" range of -128 to 255 that may be used partially depending on which union member is accessed.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Any function handling this union type would have to deal with integers in this complete range.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] More generally, the only valid operations on a union type are operations that are valid on *both* types being unioned.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] C's "union" concept is similar to union types, but is not typesafe, as it permits operations that are valid on *either* type, rather than *both*.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Union types are important in program analysis, where they are used to represent symbolic values whose exact nature (e.g., value or type) is not known.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the union of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the ancestor type.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The union of sibling types is a subtype of their common ancestor (that is, all operations permitted on their common ancestor are permitted on the union type, but they may also have other valid operations in common).
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Existential types are frequently used in connection with record types to represent modules and abstract data types, due to their ability to separate implementation from interface.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For example, the type "T = ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }" describes a module interface that has a data member named *a* of type *X* and a function named *f* that takes a parameter of the *same* type *X* and returns an integer.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] These types are both subtypes of the more general existential type T and correspond to concrete implementation types, so any value of one of these types is a value of type T.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Given a value "t" of type "T", we know that "t.f(t.a)" is well-typed, regardless of what the abstract type *X* is.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] This gives flexibility for choosing types suited to a particular implementation, while clients that use only values of the interface type—the existential type—are isolated from these choices.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In general it's impossible for the typechecker to infer which existential type a given module belongs to.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In the above example intT { a: int; f: (int → int); } could also have the type ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Although abstract data types and modules had been implemented in programming languages for quite some time, it wasn't until 1988 that John C.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Mitchell and Gordon Plotkin established the formal theory under the slogan: "Abstract [data] types have existential type".
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The theory is a second-order typed lambda calculus similar to System F, but with existential instead of universal quantification.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In a type system with Gradual typing, variables may be assigned a type either at compile-time (which is static typing), or at runtime (which is dynamic typing).
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] This allows software developers to choose either type paradigm as appropriate, from within a single language.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Gradual typing uses a special type named *dynamic* to represent statically unknown types; gradual typing replaces the notion of type equality with a new relation called *consistency* that relates the dynamic type to every other type.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The consistency relation is symmetric but not transitive.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Many static type systems, such as those of C and Java, require *type declarations*: the programmer must explicitly associate each variable with a specific type.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Others, such as Haskell's, perform *type inference*: the compiler draws conclusions about the types of variables based on how programmers use those variables.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For example, given a function `f(x, y)` that adds `x` and `y` together, the compiler can infer that `x` and `y` must be numbers—since addition is only defined for numbers.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Thus, any call to `f` elsewhere in the program that specifies a non-numeric type (such as a string or list) as an argument would signal an error.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Numerical and string constants and expressions in code can and often do imply type in a particular context.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For example, an expression `3.14` might imply a type of floating-point, while `[1, 2, 3]` might imply a list of integers—typically an array.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Type inference is in general possible, if it is computable in the type system in question.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Moreover, even if inference is not computable in general for a given type system, inference is often possible for a large subset of real-world programs.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Haskell's type system, a version of Hindley–Milner, is a restriction of System Fω to so-called rank-1 polymorphic types, in which type inference is computable.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Most Haskell compilers allow arbitrary-rank polymorphism as an extension, but this makes type inference not computable.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] A type system that assigns types to terms in type environments using typing rules is naturally associated with the decision problems of type checking, typability, and type inhabitation.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Some languages like C# or Scala have a unified type system.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] This means that all C# types including primitive types inherit from a single root object.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Every type in C# inherits from the Object class.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Some languages, like Java and Raku, have a root type but also have primitive types that are not objects.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Java provides wrapper object types that exist together with the primitive types so developers can use either the wrapper object types or the simpler non-object primitive types.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Raku automatically converts primitive types to objects when their methods are accessed.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] A type checker for a statically typed language must verify that the type of any expression is consistent with the type expected by the context in which that expression appears.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] For example, in an assignment statement of the form `x := *e*`, the inferred type of the expression *`e`* must be consistent with the declared or inferred type of the variable `x`.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] This notion of consistency, called *compatibility*, is specific to each programming language.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] If the type of *`e`* and the type of `x` are the same, and assignment is allowed for that type, then this is a valid expression.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Thus, in the simplest type systems, the question of whether two types are compatible reduces to that of whether they are *equal* (or *equivalent*).
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Different languages, however, have different criteria for when two type expressions are understood to denote the same type.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] In languages with subtyping, the compatibility relation is more complex: If `B` is a subtype of `A`, then a value of type `B` can be used in a context where one of type `A` is expected (covariant), even if the reverse is not true.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] Like equivalence, the subtype relation is defined differently for each programming language, with many variations possible.
[src:ballerina-deep/type-system] The presence of parametric or ad hoc polymorphism in a language may also have implications for type compatibility.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] WSO2 is a global technology company that develops foundational platforms for enterprises to meet their agentic needs.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] Founded in 2005, the company provides tools that enable organizations to build, connect, and manage digital services and systems across cloud and on-premises environments.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] WSO2’s product offerings include platforms for integration, identity and access management, and API management, as well as tools that support the development and deployment of applications and services.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] The company is headquartered in Sri Lanka and operates internationally, serving enterprise customers across multiple industries.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] WSO2’s software is distributed under open-source licenses and is designed to support open standards and interoperability.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] WSO2 was founded by Sanjiva Weerawarana, Paul Fremantle, and Davanum Srinivas in August 2005, backed by Intel Capital, Toba Capital, and Pacific Controls.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] Weerawarana was an IBM researcher and a founder of the Web services platform.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] He led the creation of IBM SOAP4J, which later became Apache SOAP, and was the architect of other notable projects.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] Fremantle was one of the authors of IBM's Web Services Invocation Framework and the Web Services Gateway.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] An Apache member since the original Apache SOAP project, Fremantle oversaw the donation of WSIF and WSDL4J to Apache and led IBM's involvement in the Axis C/C++ project.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] Fremantle was WSO2's chief technology officer (CTO) from 2008-2020, and was named one of *InfoWorld*'s Top 25 CTOs his first year in the role.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] Currently, Fremantle serves as a consultant for multiple technology companies, including WSO2.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] In 2017, Tyler Jewell took over as CEO while Weerawarana focused on the Ballerina open-source project.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] In 2019, Vinny Smith became the Executive Chairman.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] Weerawarana returned to the role of CEO in 2020.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] A subsidiary, WSO2Mobile, was launched in 2013, with Harsha Purasinghe of Microimage as the CEO and co-founder.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] In March 2015, WSO2.Telco was launched in partnership with Malaysian telecommunications company Axiata, which held a majority stake in the venture.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] WSO2Mobile has since been re-absorbed into its parent company.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] EQT AB's Asian private fund EQT Private Capital Asia acquired the company for over $600 million in May 2024.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] The acquisition was completed three months later.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] In 2006, Intel Capital invested $4 million in WSO2, and continued to invest in subsequent years.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] In 2010, Godel Technologies invested in WSO2 for an unspecified amount, and in 2012 the company raised a third round of $10 million.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] Official WSO2 records point to this being from Toba Capital, Cisco, and Intel Capital.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] In August 2015, a funding round led by Pacific Controls and Toba raised another $20 million.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] In November 2021, WSO2 obtained $90 million in financing from Goldman Sachs Asset Management Private Credit.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] In May 2022, WSO2 completed its Series E funding with an additional $93 million investment from Info Edge.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] Historically, WSO2 has had a close connection to the Apache community, with a significant portion of their products based on or contributing to the Apache product stack.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] Likewise, many of WSO2's top leadership have contributed to Apache projects.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] In 2013, WSO2 donated its Stratos project to Apache.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] WSO2 first introduced Ballerina, an open-source, general-purpose concurrent and strongly typed programming language with both textual and graphical syntaxes, optimized for integration in 2017.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] General availability of Ballerina 1.0 at https://ballerina.io was then announced in 2019.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] In a March 2023 product review, *InfoWorld* rated Ballerina 2201.4.0 (Swan Lake) 4 stars (out of a possible 5).
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] WSO2 provides a range of software platforms focused on API management, integration, identity and access management, agent management, and platform engineering.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] These offerings are intended to support organizations in modernizing existing IT systems by enabling interoperability between legacy infrastructure and cloud-based environments.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] The platforms facilitate the integration of disparate systems, management of digital interactions, and incremental adoption of artificial intelligence capabilities, including support for agent-based architectures.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] As of 2023, WSO2 has offices in: Mountain View, California; Austin, Texas; London, UK; São Paulo, Brazil; Sydney, Australia; Munich, Germany; Dubai, United Arab Emirates; Mumbai, India; Singapore, and Colombo, Sri Lanka.
[src:ballerina-deep/wso2] The bulk of its research and operations are conducted from its main office in Colombo.
